  "prompt": "Relation between change in celcius to change in fahrenhiet?",
  "response": "The relationship between changes in temperature in Celsius and Fahrenheit can be expressed with the following formula:\n\n\\[\n\\Delta F = \\Delta C \\times \\frac{9}{5}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\(\\Delta F\\) is the change in temperature in Fahrenheit,\n- \\(\\Delta C\\) is the change in temperature in Celsius.\n\nThis means that for every 1 degree change in Celsius, there is a corresponding change of 1.8 degrees (or \\( \\frac{9}{5} \\)) in Fahrenheit. \n\nFor example, if the temperature increases by 10 degrees Celsius, the equivalent change in Fahrenheit would be:\n\n\\[\n\\Delta F = 10 \\times \\frac{9}{5} = 18 \\text{ degrees Fahrenheit}\n\\]",
